4.42/5  rDev -3.1%look: 4 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4 |  overall: 4.52015 vintage
750ml bottle poured into a snifter
A- pours a deep black with a little bit of light creeping through, small fizzy off-white head has short retention
S- aroma up front has similarities to a Mexican spiced shout. Opens with big mix of coffee, cinnamon and chocolate, with a green pepper note, perhaps from the coffee addition. Undertones of bourbon, vanilla & toasted coconut 
T- opens with an nice mix of coffee and chocolate, followed by ginger & cinnamon, and that green pepper note from the aroma. Barrel notes are light on the bourbon, but bring out plenty of vanilla & coconut, as well as some caramel. The finish lingers of coffee and more ginger 
M- medium body with moderate-low carbonation leads to a foamy mouthfeel and finish 
O- barrel aging and coffee addition add welcomed compliment to an already awesome Christmas beer 851 charactersTreyliff, Dec 25, 2016
4.45/5  rDev -2.4%look: 4 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.25 |  overall: 4.5Yet another fantastic version of Gingerbread Stout. I loved Christmas Morning, but KY Christmas Morning is even better. The gingerbread base still comes through, but you pick up a little coffee and just enough bourbon barrel. 225 charactersCpmitchno1, Dec 25, 2016
4.37/5  rDev -4.2%look: 3.75 | smell: 4.25 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.25 |  overall: 4.5The beer pours a very light head that dissipates very quickly. The beer itself is a dark chocolate black because that how pretty much every friggin' stout looks like pretty much. The texture is a lot more interesting though. It has the appearance of an oily and heavy look that you normally see with hard liquor. IT's not a bad look but it does take away from the experience a bit.
The smell is good. It has a strong bourbon note supplemented by some strong spice notes such cinnamon and clove with a bit of vanilla supplementing it.
The taste is fantastic. It has a strong Kentucky bourbon note that completely dominates the other notes. While the other notes have a nice strength to them that adds a nice extra something to it. The coffee note is light but strong and bitter enough to add something interesting. The honey note is strong but it gets lost in the bourbon. The beer has a good moderate vanilla note that makes it fairly visible among the different spices (cinnamon, a bit of clove). It's actually pretty good for an imperial milk stout.
The feel is pretty good. It's a fairly heavy body beer but it feels much more smoother with a slight syrupy feel that you normally find in bourbon. The carbonation is extremely light and tingly that it keeps the beer from being too smooth.
Overall, this is a pretty good beer. The look is okay but the real appeal of this beer is in the taste. While I wouldn't go to the ends of the Earth for this beer, it's definitely one worth trying at least once. 1,507 charactersHattedClassic, Dec 25, 2016
