4.35/5  rDev -4.6%look: 4 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.25 | feel: 4.25 |  overall: 4.5Appearance - As with the rest of Hardywood's line of gingerbread stouts, Kentucky Christmas Morning pours a glossy black color with a dark brown head. The head is rather long-lasting with somewhat spotty lacing. Otherwise, this is a fairly typical looking stout.
Aroma - The nose is absolutely spot-on in terms of nailing a boozy interpretation of what Christmas morning should be like. There's a festive blend of spices led by the predominant ginger that Hardywood is so renowned for. Next is a nice bourbon, oak, and vanilla blend that adds a lot of depth. Rounding out the aroma is a bittersweet chocolate and freshly ground coffee note.
Taste - It may seem repitative at this point, but it seems like any beer that Hardywood makes that contains ginger is, for better or worse, a ginger bomb. Personally, I love that aspect of these beers since the dichotomy between the ginger and stout flavors is addicting to me. One downside to this is that it tends to crowd out some of the other flavors, especially the adjuncts in this beer. The bourbon is pretty mild, and the coffee is sort of non-existent until the finish.
Mouthfeel - The body is pretty thick with a slick feel and medium carbonation.
Closing Arguments - Overall, this is another solid addition to Hardywood's Gingerbread Stout line. My only detractions would be that the bourbon isn't as forward as I would've liked, and especially the coffee could've been ramped up more. Otherwise, it is a very solid ginger stout and epitomises a Christmas-style beer. 1,523 charactersnhindian, Mar 22, 2016
